.SS Source\-Dependent Expressions
.sp
The source file, as specified in the following expressions, can be nonexistent
on the file system (i.e. generated file) but must be known from CMake. A source
file becomes known from CMake if it is part of some target (library or
executable) or when a source file property is defined. Moreover, this
information is specific to the directory where the declaration occurred.
.sp
For example, these generator expressions enable to offer a uniform behavior,
for the \fBadd_custom_command()\fP \%<#\:command:add_custom_command> and \fBadd_custom_target()\fP \%<#\:command:add_custom_target>
commands, regarding the source properties:
.INDENT 0.0
.INDENT 3.5
.sp
.EX
function(custom_add_library target)
  unset(sources)
  foreach(source IN LISTS ARGN)
    add_custom_command(
      OUTPUT ${CMAKE_CURRENT_BINARY_DIR}/${source}.bin
      COMMAND my\-compiler \-o ${CMAKE_CURRENT_BINARY_DIR}/${source}.bin
                          \(dq$<$<SOURCE_EXISTS:${source}>:$<SOURCE_PROPERTY:${source},COMPILE_OPTIONS>>\(dq
                          ${source})
    list(APPEND sources ${CMAKE_CURRENT_BINARY_DIR}/${source}.bin)
  endforeach()
  add_custom_target(${target}
                    DEPENDS ${sources})
endfunction()

custom_add_library(my\-lib file1.x file2.x file3.x)
set_property(SOURCE file1.x PROPERTY COMPILE_OPTIONS \-X)
set_property(SOURCE file2.x PROPERTY COMPILE_OPTIONS \-Y)
.EE
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Source Meta\-Data
.sp
These expressions look up information about a source file.
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<SOURCE_EXISTS:src[,(DIRECTORY:dir|TARGET_DIRECTORY:tgt)]>
Added in version 4.3.

.sp
\fB1\fP if \fBsrc\fP exists as a CMake source file, else \fB0\fP\&. By default, the
source file is searched in the scope of the current source directory or the
directory of the consuming target.
.sp
Directory scope can be overridden with one of the following sub\-options:
.INDENT 7.0
.TP
.B \fBDIRECTORY:dir\fP
The source file will be searched in the \fBdir\fP directory\(aqs scope.
CMake must know about the directory, either by having added  it through a
call to \fBadd_subdirectory()\fP \%<#\:command:add_subdirectory> or \fBdir\fP being the top level
directory. Relative paths are treated as relative to the current source
directory.
.TP
.B \fBTARGET_DIRECTORY:target\fP
The source file will be searched in the directory scope in which
\fBtarget\fP was created (\fBtarget\fP must therefore exist).
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Source Properties
.sp
These expressions look up the values of
source file properties \%<#\:source-file-properties>\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<SOURCE_PROPERTY:src[,(DIRECTORY:dir|TARGET_DIRECTORY:target)],prop>
Added in version 4.3.

.sp
Value of the property \fBprop\fP on the source file \fBsrc\fP, or empty if
the property is not set. An error will be raised if the source file is not
known by CMake. By default, the source file\(aqs property will be read from the
current source directory\(aqs scope or the directory of the consuming target.
.sp
Directory scope can be overridden with one of the following sub\-options:
.INDENT 7.0
.TP
.B \fBDIRECTORY:dir\fP
The source file property will be read from the \fBdir\fP directory\(aqs scope.
CMake must know about the directory, either by having added  it through a
call to \fBadd_subdirectory()\fP \%<#\:command:add_subdirectory> or \fBdir\fP being the top level
directory. Relative paths are treated as relative to the current source
directory.
.TP
.B \fBTARGET_DIRECTORY:target\fP
The source file property will be read from the directory scope in which
\fBtarget\fP was created (\fBtarget\fP must therefore exist).
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS FileSet\-Dependent Expressions
.SS FileSet Meta\-Data
.sp
These expressions look up information about a file set.
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<FILE_SET_EXISTS:fileset,TARGET:target>
Added in version 4.3.

.sp
\fB1\fP if the \fBfileset\fP exists as a CMake file set attached to the
\fBtarget\fP, else \fB0\fP\&.
.sp
The possible sub\-options are:
.INDENT 7.0
.TP
.B \fBTARGET:target\fP
The target on which the file set depends.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS FileSet Properties
.sp
These expressions look up the values of file set properties.
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<FILE_SET_PROPERTY:fileset,TARGET:target,prop>
Added in version 4.3.

.sp
Value of the property \fBprop\fP on the file set \fBfileset\fP, or empty if
the property is not set. An error will be raised if the file set is not
known by CMake.
.sp
The possible sub\-options are:
.INDENT 7.0
.TP
.B \fBTARGET:target\fP
The target on which the file set depends.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.SS Target\-Dependent Expressions
.SS Target Meta\-Data
.sp
These expressions look up information about a target.
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<TARGET_EXISTS:tgt>
Added in version 3.12.

.sp
\fB1\fP if \fBtgt\fP exists as a CMake target, else \fB0\fP\&.
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<TARGET_NAME_IF_EXISTS:tgt>
Added in version 3.12.

.sp
The target name \fBtgt\fP if the target exists, an empty string otherwise.
.sp
Note that \fBtgt\fP is not added as a dependency of the target this
expression is evaluated on.
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<TARGET_NAME:tgt>
The target name \fBtgt\fP as written.  This marks \fBtgt\fP as being the name
of a target inside a larger expression, which is required if exporting
targets to multiple dependent export sets.  The \fBtgt\fP text must be a
literal name of a target; it may not contain generator expressions.
The target does not have to exist.
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<TARGET_POLICY:policy>
\fB1\fP if the \fBpolicy\fP was \fBNEW\fP when the \(aqhead\(aq target was created,
else \fB0\fP\&.  If the \fBpolicy\fP was not set, the warning message for the policy
will be emitted. This generator expression only works for a subset of
policies.
.UNINDENT
.SS Target Properties
.sp
These expressions look up the values of
target properties \%<#\:target-properties>\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<TARGET_PROPERTY:tgt,prop>
Value of the property \fBprop\fP on the target \fBtgt\fP, or empty if
the property is not set.
.sp
Note that \fBtgt\fP is not added as a dependency of the target this
expression is evaluated on.
.sp
Changed in version 3.26: When encountered during evaluation of Target Usage Requirements \%<#\:target-usage-requirements>,
typically in an \fBINTERFACE_*\fP target property, lookup of the \fBtgt\fP
name occurs in the directory of the target specifying the requirement,
rather than the directory of the consuming target for which the
expression is being evaluated.

.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<TARGET_PROPERTY:prop>
Value of the property \fBprop\fP on the target for which the expression
is being evaluated, or empty if the property is not set.
Note that for generator expressions in Target Usage Requirements \%<#\:target-usage-requirements>
this is the consuming target rather than the target specifying the
requirement.
.UNINDENT
.sp
The expressions have special evaluation rules for some properties:
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B Target Build Specification Properties \%<#\:target-build-specification>
These evaluate as a semicolon\-separated list \%<#\:cmake-language-lists>
representing the union of the value on the target itself with the values
of the corresponding Target Usage Requirements \%<#\:target-usage-requirements> on targets named by
the target\(aqs \fBLINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:LINK_LIBRARIES>:
.INDENT 7.0
.IP \(bu 2
For Target Compile Properties \%<#\:target-compile-properties>, evaluation of corresponding usage
requirements is transitive over the closure of the linked targets\(aq
\fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES> \fIexcluding\fP entries guarded by the
\fBLINK_ONLY\fP generator expression.
.IP \(bu 2
For Target Link Properties \%<#\:target-link-properties>, evaluation of corresponding usage
requirements is transitive over the closure of the linked targets\(aq
\fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES> \fIincluding\fP entries guarded by the
\fBLINK_ONLY\fP generator expression.  See policy \fBCMP0166\fP \%<#\:policy:CMP0166>\&.
.UNINDENT
.sp
Changed in version 4.1: Evaluation of \fBLINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:LINK_LIBRARIES> itself is now transitive.
See policy \fBCMP0189\fP \%<#\:policy:CMP0189>\&.

.TP
.B Target Usage Requirement Properties \%<#\:target-usage-requirements>
These evaluate as a semicolon\-separated list \%<#\:cmake-language-lists>
representing the union of the value on the target itself with the values
of the same properties on targets named by the target\(aqs
\fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>:
.INDENT 7.0
.IP \(bu 2
For Transitive Compile Properties \%<#\:transitive-compile-properties>, evaluation is transitive over
the closure of the target\(aqs \fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>
\fIexcluding\fP entries guarded by the \fBLINK_ONLY\fP generator expression.
.IP \(bu 2
For Transitive Link Properties \%<#\:transitive-link-properties>, evaluation is transitive over
the closure of the target\(aqs \fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>
\fIincluding\fP entries guarded by the \fBLINK_ONLY\fP generator expression.
See policy \fBCMP0166\fP \%<#\:policy:CMP0166>\&.
.UNINDENT
.sp
Changed in version 4.1: Evaluation of \fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES> itself is now
transitive.  See policy \fBCMP0189\fP \%<#\:policy:CMP0189>\&.

.TP
.B Custom Transitive Properties \%<#\:custom-transitive-properties>
Added in version 3.30.

.sp
These are processed during evaluation as follows:
.INDENT 7.0
.IP \(bu 2
Evaluation of \fB$<TARGET_PROPERTY:tgt,PROP>\fP for some property
\fBPROP\fP, named without an \fBINTERFACE_\fP prefix,
checks the \fBTRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES>
and \fBTRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES> properties on target \fBtgt\fP,
on targets named by its \fBLINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:LINK_LIBRARIES>, and on the
transitive closure of targets named by the linked targets\(aq
\fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>\&.
.sp
If \fBPROP\fP is listed by one of those properties, then it evaluates as
a semicolon\-separated list \%<#\:cmake-language-lists> representing
the union of the value on the target itself with the values of the
corresponding \fBINTERFACE_PROP\fP on targets named by the target\(aqs
\fBLINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:LINK_LIBRARIES>:
.INDENT 2.0
.IP \(bu 2
If \fBPROP\fP is named by \fBTRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES>,
evaluation of the corresponding \fBINTERFACE_PROP\fP is transitive over
the closure of the linked targets\(aq \fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>,
excluding entries guarded by the \fBLINK_ONLY\fP generator expression.
.IP \(bu 2
If \fBPROP\fP is named by \fBTRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES>,
evaluation of the corresponding \fBINTERFACE_PROP\fP is transitive over
the closure of the linked targets\(aq \fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>,
including entries guarded by the \fBLINK_ONLY\fP generator expression.
.UNINDENT
.IP \(bu 2
Evaluation of \fB$<TARGET_PROPERTY:tgt,INTERFACE_PROP>\fP for some
property \fBINTERFACE_PROP\fP, named with an \fBINTERFACE_\fP prefix,
checks the \fBTRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES>
and \fBTRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES> properties on target \fBtgt\fP,
and on the transitive closure of targets named by its
\fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>\&.
.sp
If the corresponding \fBPROP\fP is listed by one of those properties,
then \fBINTERFACE_PROP\fP evaluates as a
semicolon\-separated list \%<#\:cmake-language-lists> representing the
union of the value on the target itself with the value of the same
property on targets named by the target\(aqs
\fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>:
.INDENT 2.0
.IP \(bu 2
If \fBPROP\fP is named by \fBTRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES>,
evaluation of the corresponding \fBINTERFACE_PROP\fP is transitive over
the closure of the target\(aqs \fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>,
excluding entries guarded by the \fBLINK_ONLY\fP generator expression.
.IP \(bu 2
If \fBPROP\fP is named by \fBTRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES>,
evaluation of the corresponding \fBINTERFACE_PROP\fP is transitive over
the closure of the target\(aqs \fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>,
including entries guarded by the \fBLINK_ONLY\fP generator expression.
.UNINDENT
.UNINDENT
.sp
If a \fBPROP\fP is named by both \fBTRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_COMPILE_PROPERTIES>
and \fBTRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:TRANSITIVE_LINK_PROPERTIES>, the latter takes precedence.
.TP
.B Compatible Interface Properties \%<#\:compatible-interface-properties>
These evaluate as a single value combined from the target itself,
from targets named by the target\(aqs \fBLINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:LINK_LIBRARIES>, and
from the transitive closure of the linked targets\(aq
\fBINTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES\fP \%<#\:prop_tgt:INTERFACE_LINK_LIBRARIES>\&.  Values of a compatible
interface property from multiple targets combine based on the type
of compatibility required by the \fBCOMPATIBLE_INTERFACE_*\fP property
defining it.
.UNINDENT
.SS Target Artifacts
.sp
These expressions look up information about artifacts associated with
a given target \fBtgt\fP\&.  Unless otherwise stated, this can be any
runtime artifact, namely:
.INDENT 0.0
.IP \(bu 2
An executable target created by \fBadd_executable()\fP \%<#\:command:add_executable>\&.
.IP \(bu 2
A shared library target (\fB\&.so\fP, \fB\&.dll\fP but not their \fB\&.lib\fP import
library) created by \fBadd_library()\fP \%<#\:command:add_library>\&.
.IP \(bu 2
A static library target created by \fBadd_library()\fP \%<#\:command:add_library>\&.
.UNINDENT
.sp
In the following, the phrase \(dqthe \fBtgt\fP filename\(dq means the name of the
\fBtgt\fP binary file. This has to be distinguished from the phrase
\(dqthe target name\(dq, which is just the string \fBtgt\fP\&.
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<TARGET_FILE:tgt>
Full path to the \fBtgt\fP binary file.
.sp
Note that \fBtgt\fP is not added as a dependency of the target this
expression is evaluated on, unless the expression is being used in
\fBadd_custom_command()\fP \%<#\:command:add_custom_command> or \fBadd_custom_target()\fP \%<#\:command:add_custom_target>\&.
.UNINDENT
.INDENT 0.0
.TP
.B $<TARGET_FILE_BASE_NAME:tgt[,POSTFIX:(INCLUDE|EXCLUDE)]>
